<br>
A disembodied voice started to whispered to her. This voice, a male’s, spoke of danger, lies and deceit. Then, it spoke of the children of Nathomin... Malaehi was stricken with fear and doubt. But, the voice lead her into the lair of the Teir’dals, into the Library of Neriak, where she read more of the history of the House T’Vlos and the tales of Nathomin therein. Malaehi’s illusion wavered as she was washed over with grief. “Oh, Nathomin... why did you not tell me... you fathered children, and ... with... her...“ <br>
<br>
She chanted an incantation and stepped into the pale blue shadows, appearing in her room in Felwithe. Solitude was needed, she needed time to think... the one thing she has not done this entire time. She had been so blinded by her mission that she did not see the trap that lay before her; the trap of her heart and of her awakened passion. <br>
<br>
The voice began to haunt Malaehi, no matter where she went ... the voice followed. Here is was again, whispering to her, warning her... Malaehi drops to her knees in madness, screaming: “WHO ARE YOU?!“ Her voice echoed in the small chamber of her room. The voice finally responded with a chuckle and answered: “You know who this is, fair one and you know I speak the truth.“ Malaehi jumped to her feet, spun around shouting: “Show yourself, NOW, daemon!“ She was indeed alone.<br>
<br>
For a week, Malaehi prayed and prayed, begging for the voice to leave her alone, so she could worship... so she could think of what to do. But, it persisted, driving her mad. Occasionally, she would her Nathomin’s voice call to her, searching for her, then the voice would be Mallo’s or was it Kylaa’s, then it would be her enemy Jyssa jeering at her, “The Chaste one... HA! More like chased!” She heard her disapproving voice of Tintari, changing into the voice of concern from her twin Ennya. Malaehi crawled into her bed, with her pillow over her head, crying herself to sleep, begging for this torment to end, crying out for her lover to be with her, to hold her.<br>
<br>
Vivid dreams plagued her sleep, her lover hunted down like a madman, tortured, interrogated and executed. Malaehi envisioned herself standing on a precipice, teetering on the edge, no escape, no right way to go, no one to advise nor help. Giving into this feeling of love means losing the only stable things in her life: her service of her Goddess and her brethren in Coeur de Lion. However, the other option, to forsake the one she has given so much for, who has left his way of life to pursue her, who has humbled himself before her Goddess ... the one whom she now knows ... she loves ... <br>
<br>
Malaehi awoke with a start, flailing in the sheets as if she were falling. Scrambling out of her bed, she ran down the hallway, barefoot and wrapped in her sheet. Bursting through the doors that lead to the courtyard, she ran straight to the fountain in the center, and fell into the water. On her knees, soaked to the skin, she raised her eyes up to the statue of Erollisi Marr. There her Goddess’ image stood, arms gently holding the image of Norrath ...<br>
<br>
Mala cried out in desperation: “Dear precious Goddess, must I choose my love or my brethren? Is there no other way?” She was answered with the gentle lapping of the waves in the pool where she knelt. <br>
<br>
Fresh tears sprung from her eyes as she tore the sheet covering her in two, tears of frustration and madness. Disheveled and naked, Malaehi walked back into her quarters, pulled out her pristine white gossamer robe, arranged her hair in the High Elven fashion, and walked out of her room, leaving the rest of her belongings behind. <br>
<br>
Dawn arrived as she was boarding the ship bound for Kunark ... her mind was completely blank, spent from all the agony. A human passenger tried to strike up conversation with the dazed Enchantress. She saw his lips moving, by all she heard was the whispers in her mind, haunting her again with a terrifying chuckle... <br>
<br>
